Management Revolution or the End of Economic Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of the major French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence would have been futile...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees reminds us of the position of the companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is to make employees adhere to certain "values" from above, as it was used by the technicians to impose on consumers.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquering the markets in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose disconnected products from customer preference factors regularly comes back!
Employee demobilization can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects managers in particular.
This demobilization seriously undermines the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, including R&D and, moreover, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the IE "requires from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires on the part of employees a commitment that authoritarian management revenues totally contradict.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would be to put employees at the center of the company’s concerns in the same way as the customer.
The Relative Use of Internal Opinion Surveys
Will internal opinion polls – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incite this revolution in managerial practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all, because I have been able to find that, in the face of a new situation, any structure finally arrives, after many deviations, to do priority... what she has always done.
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
From the great schools of engineers, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the "neurosciences" of the United States and widely disseminated, unknowingly, by the institutes of study and the media.
Thus, suggesting that it is possible to handle the "leverages" (sic) of manager engagement, a recent survey of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr comforts leaders in a mechanistic, unsuitable position of governance in today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises requires a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental conclusion: for employees, engagement with the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a way to realize part of their dreams, ambitions, and projects.
Currently, only studies from the Motion-Functional Analysis adopt this concept of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life plans.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "in place".
They thus create a ground for the concerted development of a robust and effective economic intelligence.
