The cradle of dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled the other carnivore dinosaurs: this bipedal was about 2 meters long by 1.50m high, its rear limbs were powerful, its elongated skull had sharp and curved teeth, its short arms ended with clawed claws, and it had a lounge.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and his colleagues report in Thursday's Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs to have these morphological characteristics.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which was then part of the emerging lands of the supercontinent, the Pangaea, and was in the direction of the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa enlightens a new day the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
In fact, it informs us about the relationships, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists on the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and member of the excavation team tells us that sometimes they find a dozen bones in a day, which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating from the Trias.
Scientists quickly realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
The excavations updated the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms the theories about the beginnings of dinosaur evolution.
The researchers named him Tawa after the word of the Indians Hopi for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Trias are extremely rare and limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all experts in paleontology share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he notes that it confirms certain theories concerning the beginnings of dinosaur evolution.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, which makes it very difficult to classify all the first dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the Saurians were divided into three major evolutionary groups: the theropods (carnivores) which comprise the tyrannosaurus and the velociraptor that appeared later and whose descendants the birds, the sauropods, the quadrupeds of which the snips are long-necked, and those whose parts are the aparigots and theirs.
According to studies by S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa is one of the first theeropods.
This species presents an interesting report of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
The researchers found clues that suggest that the Tawa hallae had small airbags in its bones at the skull level, just like the birds that are descendants of the theropods.
These small air pockets make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It seems that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theeropods with small air bags in its bones.
Since the related lineage of huge sauropods also had airbags and a light bone, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three consecutive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, researchers concluded that the Saurians had appeared there.
Therefore, the three major lines of evolution were divided and spread from South America to the rest of the world, that is, all the emerging lands that formed the Pangaean supercontinent.
This appears to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
The three species cannot descend from a common ancestor who would have migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there would have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says that there is an even older species, the silesaurus, that lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a wrong view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while practically none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how the dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapods of the secondary age as they came from a relatively rare sideline of the reptiles branch remains a mystery to this day.
At the time of the Trias, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as with the ancestors of the current crocodiles and with many other Saurians.
By the end of the Trias, dinosaurs spread across the planet, thus promoting the development of many new species, while others, who were related to them, disappeared between the Trias and the Jurassic.
Such a success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There could have been a massive extinction at which the dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles had disappeared.
Or, at the time, dinosaurs were better suited and thus they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such a success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favored the development of a group of animals that had also developed during the Trias and that since then was vegetated in the shadow: it was mammals.
