75% of working mothers have had occupational problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of young generations who want to be mothers.
This is what the study “Women’s Fertility and Professional Career in Spain” carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer reveals.
The survey, which was conducted on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers saw their careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of couple life and the number of children, whether the woman is working or not, and the type of employment employed.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier, and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are pushing back into couple life and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between the ages of 35 and 49 with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after they have settled in a couple. This figure increases to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. “These data show that women with a stable job needed more time in their lives to get it together and get it back to them.
In addition, the type of employment exerted greatly influences maternity, but less the start date of common life,” explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that diverges between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those who completed elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average, respectively.
“Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have completed elementary studies get married and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child.
