CNMV Authorizes Paternina Exclusion OPA Presented by Inversora Mer
The National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) authorised yesterday the exclusion OPA presented by Inversora Mer on Federico Paternina on 9 October last.
The supervisory body explained that it authorised this operation because it understood that its terms were aligned with the standards in force and that it considered the content of the explanatory leaflet submitted “sufficiency” following the amendments applied on 2 December.
The CNMV stated that the offer concerns the acquisition of 550 008 shares of Federico Paternina at a price of 7.65 euros per share, representing 8.95 % of the share capital, consisting of 6,142,786 shares admitted to trading on the Madrid and Bilbao stock exchanges.
In addition, he explained that 5,592,778 million shares were immobilized and could not be transferred in any way before the end of the offer, which he indicated was priced by Federico Paternina, in accordance with the provisions of the current standards.
New tools for the expertise of cars
In these days of bad weather and accidents, car garages are not the only winners.
Every day, thousands of cars that have been injured are brought back to a garage, where an expert has to evaluate the damage suffered and the cost of repair.
Each accident is different, and calculating the cost of parts and working time can be a long and complex work.
Calculating by hand the cost of a repair between 20,000 and 30,000 euros, including the parts and the workforce can take two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the assistance of the latest computer tools, it would be a matter of minutes.
That’s why almost 100% of experts use this type of system.
Disaster Assessment and Maintenance Services and Solutions Providers are committed to collecting information provided by manufacturers, then processing it and offering it to their customers in the form of a useful tool.
In Spain, Audatex, of the North American group Solera, is the leading company; 80% of the estimates are made with its products.
Other companies competing in the field of assessment tools and sector information development are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with data provided by manufacturers is far from simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, commercial director of Audatex, the company in Spain with 63 manufacturers and importers, and each of them provides them with information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed continues to increase, so over the last five years more versions, variants and engines have been launched than in the previous fifteen years.
When a new car comes out on the market, these companies get to work.
This is a very hard job, because you need to catalog each of the thousand parts of the vehicle and register its price.
In addition, a “intelligent” graphic image of each model is established on which one can click on the different parts of a tourist car.
If it is a massively sold model, the work can be done in a week if the process progresses very quickly.
If it is a small car, it can take three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information on 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the most exclusive models, they have information about the Porsche, for example, but not the Ferrari or the Lamborghini.
In the case of vehicles in circulation, the figure exceeds 99%.
To carry out the work of documentation and database development, Audatex has eight centers worldwide (in Spain, France, Germany, the United States, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them specializes in certain brands.
The National Headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics experts) work simultaneously on three computer screens.
Audatex invests <0x24>90 million each year to develop these databases.
Every month, 2.5 million data are recorded, and customers receive updates every two days.
The development of this huge flow of information allows these companies to give them different uses and offer various products.
The most common application relates to repair and maintenance, but depending on the country, there are also tools for handling broken parts or for calculating the venal or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer it in our country, but it does in the United States.
In view of the products offered by Audatex, it is easy to get an idea of the type of support it can provide to industry professionals.
This company offers ten different tools, the flagship product being AudaPlus, the standard disaster assessment solution for experts.
There are cars, motorcycles, light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it takes into account the estimated repair times by the manufacturer or the paint bars.
This tool is purchased according to its use, for each estimate.
The highest cost is 5.75 euros, for customers who use it little, up to ten times a month.
Then, each insurance company, which carries out thousands of expertise, negotiates its price with Audatex.
Other products, such as AudaVIN, allow the total identification of a vehicle and the equipment with which it came out of the assembly line, only thanks to its chassis number.
AudaGlass focuses on vehicle glasses, and AudaSubastas is an open server for the professional sector on the Internet that allows you to auction on vehicles declared to be destroyed.
Its statistical service is very useful in identifying trends, conducting geo-demographic analyses or knowing common problems by brand or model.
It is possible to study, for example, how many models of a particular brand went to the garage for a breakdown or how many suffered serious accidents for a given period.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of tools.
It sells, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for experts and provides digital images, as well as access to the manufacturer’s official parts, prices and times.
